Perfect! Now I can see the issue clearly. The `add(T[] array, T element)` method should throw an `IllegalArgumentException` when both arguments are null, but currently it doesn't check for this condition. Looking at the code:

```java
public static <T> T[] add(T[] array, T element) {
    Class<?> type;
    if (array != null){
        type = array.getClass();
    } else if (element != null) {
        type = element.getClass();
    } else {
        type = Object.class;  // This is the case when both array and element are null
    }
    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked") // type must be T
    T[] newArray = (T[]) copyArrayGrow1(array, type);
    newArray[newArray.length - 1] = element;  // This sets the element to null
    return newArray;
}
```

When both `array` and `element` are null, it creates a new array with one null element, which is not the expected behavior according to the test. The test expects an `IllegalArgumentException` to be thrown.

Let me also check if there's an overloaded version with an index that also has this issue:

